SIMPLE: for
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: For-
<hw>For-</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <ety>[AS. <ets>for-</ets>; akin to D. & G.
<ets>ver</ets>-, OHG. <ets>fir</ets>-, Icel. <ets>for</ets>-, Goth.
<ets>fra</ets>-, cf. Skr. <ets>par⟦amac⟧-</ets> away, Gr. <?/ beside,
and E. <ets>far</ets>, adj. Cf. <er>Fret</er> to rub.]</ety> <def>A
prefix to verbs, having usually the force of a negative or privative. It
often implies also <xex>loss</xex>, <xex>detriment</xex>, or
<xex>destruction</xex>, and sometimes it is intensive, meaning
<xex>utterly</xex>, <xex>quite thoroughly</xex>, as in
<xex>for</xex>bathe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>For</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: For
<hw>For</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prep.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>for</ets>,
<ets>fore</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>for</ets>, <ets>fora</ets>,
<ets>furi</ets>, D. <ets>voor</ets>, OHG. <ets>fora</ets>, G.
<ets>vor</ets>, OHG. <ets>furi</ets>, G. <ets>f⟦uum⟧r</ets>, Icel.
<ets>fyrir</ets>, Sw. <ets>f⟦oum⟧r</ets>, Dan. <ets>for</ets>, adv.
<ets>f⟦oum⟧r</ets>, Goth. <ets>fa⟦uacute⟧r</ets>,
<ets>fa⟦uacute⟧ra</ets>, L. <ets>pro</ets>, Gr. <?/, Skr.
<ets>pra</ets>-. ⟦root⟧ 202. Cf. <er>Fore</er>, <er>First</er>,
<er>Foremost</er>, <er>Forth</er>, <er>Pro-</er>.]</ety> <def>In the
most general sense, indicating that in consideration of, in view of, or
with reference to, which anything is done or takes place.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Indicating the antecedent cause or occasion of an
action; the motive or inducement accompanying and prompting to an act or
state; the reason of anything; that on account of which a thing is or is
done.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With fiery eyes sparkling <qex>for</qex> very wrath.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How to choose dogs <qex>for</qex> scent or speed.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now, <qex>for</qex> so many glorious actions done,⟦br⟧
<qex>For</qex> peace at home, and <qex>for</qex> the public wealth,⟦br⟧
I mean to crown a bowl <qex>for</qex> C⟦ae⟧sar's health.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That which we, <qex>for</qex> our unworthiness, are afraid to
crave, our prayer is, that God, <qex>for</qex> the worthiness of his
Son, would, notwithstanding, vouchsafe to grant.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Indicating the remoter and indirect object of an
act; the end or final cause with reference to which anything is, acts,
serves, or is done.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The oak <qex>for</qex> nothing ill,⟦br⟧
The osier good <qex>for</qex> twigs, the poplar <qex>for</qex> the
mill.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was young counsel <qex>for</qex> the persons, and violent
counsel <qex>for</qex> the matters.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall I think the worls was made <qex>for one</qex>,⟦br⟧
And men are born <qex>for</qex> kings, as beasts <qex>for</qex> men,⟦br⟧
Not <qex>for</qex> protection, but to be devoured?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For he writes not <qex>for</qex> money, nor <qex>for</qex>
praise.</q> <rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Indicating that in favor of which, or in promoting
which, anything is, or is done; hence, in behalf of; in favor of; on the
side of; -- opposed to <xex>against</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We can do nothing against the truth, but <qex>for</qex> the
truth.</q> <rj><qau>2 Cor. xiii. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is <qex>for</qex> the general good of human society, and
consequently of particular persons, to be true and just; and it is
<qex>for</qex> men's health to be temperate.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Aristotle is <qex>for</qex> poetical justice.</q>
<rj><qau>Dennis.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Indicating that toward which the action of anything
is directed, or the point toward which motion is made; intending to go
to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We sailed from Peru <qex>for</qex> China and Japan.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Indicating that on place of or instead of which
anything acts or serves, or that to which a substitute, an equivalent, a
compensation, or the like, is offered or made; instead of, or place
of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And if any mischief follow, then thou shalt give life
<qex>for</qex> life, eye <qex>for</qex> eye, tooth <qex>for</qex> tooth,
hand <qex>for</qex> hand, foot <qex>for</qex> foot.</q> <rj><qau>Ex.
xxi. 23, 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Indicating that in the character of or as being
which anything is regarded or treated; to be, or as being.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We take a falling meteor <qex>for</qex> a star.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If a man can be fully assured of anything <qex>for</qex> a truth,
without having examined, what is there that he may not embrace
<qex>for</qex> tru<?/?</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Most of our ingenious young men take up some cried-up English
poet for</qex> their model.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But let her go <qex>for</qex> an ungrateful woman.</q>
<rj><qau>Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Indicating that instead of which something else
controls in the performing of an action, or that in spite of which
anything is done, occurs, or is; hence, equivalent to
<xex>notwithstanding</xex>, <xex>in spite of</xex>; -- generally
followed by <xex>all</xex>, <xex>aught</xex>, <xex>anything</xex>,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The writer will do what she please <qex>for</qex> all me.</q>
<rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God's desertion shall, <qex>for</qex> aught he knows, the next
minute supervene.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>For</qex> anything that legally appears to the contrary, it
may be a contrivance to fright us.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Indicating the space or time through which an action
or state extends; hence, during; in or through the space or time
of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>For</qex> many miles about⟦br⟧
There 's scarce a bush.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Since, hired <qex>for</qex> life, thy servile muse sing.</q>
<rj><qau>prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To guide the sun's bright chariot <qex>for</qex> a day.</q>
<rj><qau>Garth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Indicating that in prevention of which, or through
fear of which, anything is done.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We 'll have a bib, <qex>for</qex> spoiling of thy doublet.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><mcol><col><b>For</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>As
for</b></col></mcol>, <cd>so far as concerns; as regards; with reference
to; -- used parenthetically or independently. See under
<er>As</er>.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>As for</qex> me and my house, we will serve the Lord.</q>
<rj><qau>Josh. xxiv. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>For</qex> me, my stormy voyage at an end,⟦br⟧
I to the port of death securely tend.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>For all that</b></col>, <cd>notwithstanding; in spite
of.</cd> -- <col><b>For all the world</b></col>, <cd>wholly;
exactly.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Whose posy was, <xex>for all the world</xex>, like
cutlers' poetry.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>For as much
as</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Forasmuch as</b></col></mcol>, <cd>in
consideration that; seeing that; since.</cd> -- <col><b>For
by</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Forby</er>, <pos>adv.</pos></cd> --
<col><b>For ever</b></col>, <cd>eternally; at all times. See
<er>Forever</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>For me</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>For all me</b></col></mcol>, <cd>as far as regards me.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>For my life</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>For the life of
me</b></col></mcol>, <cd>if my life depended on it.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <au>T. Hook.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>For
that</b></col>, <col><b>For the reason that</b></col></mcol>,
<cd>because; since.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>For that</xex>
I love your daughter.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>For
thy</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Forthy</b></col></mcol> <ety>[AS.
<ets>for⟦edh⟧⟦ymac⟧</ets>.]</ety>, <cd>for this; on this account.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Thomalin, have no care <xex>for
thy</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Spenser.</au> -- <col><b>For to</b></col>, <cd>as
sign of infinitive, in order to; to the end of.</cd> <mark>[Obs., except
as sometimes heard in illiterate speech.]</mark> -- ⟦ldquo⟧What went ye
out <xex>for to</xex> see?⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Luke vii. 25.</au> <see>See
<er>To</er>, <pos>prep.</pos>, 4.</see> -- <col><b>O for</b></col>,
<cd>would that I had; may there be granted; -- elliptically expressing
desire or prayer.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>O for</xex> a muse of fire.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>Were it not for</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>If it were not for</b></col></mcol>, <cd>leaving out of account;
but for the presence or action of.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Moral consideration can
no way move the sensible appetite, <xex>were it not for</xex> the
will.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir M. Hale.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>For</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: For
<hw>For</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>conj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Because; by
reason that; for that; indicating, in Old English, the reason of
anything.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>for</qex> of long that way had walk⟦eacute⟧d none,⟦br⟧
The vault was hid with plants and bushes hoar.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Heaven defend your good souls, that you think⟦br⟧
I will your serious and great business scant,⟦br⟧
<qex>For</qex> she with me.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Since; because; introducing a reason of something
before advanced, a cause, motive, explanation, justification, or the
like, of an action related or a statement made. It is logically nearly
equivalent to <xex>since</xex>, or <xex>because</xex>, but connects less
closely, and is sometimes used as a very general introduction to
something suggested by what has gone before.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give thanks unto the Lord; <qex>for</qex> he is good;
<qex>for</qex> his mercy endureth forever.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxxxvi.
1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Heaven doth with us as we with torches do,⟦br⟧
Not light them for themselves; <qex>for</qex> if our virtues⟦br⟧
Did not go forth of us, 't were all alike⟦br⟧
As if we had them not.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>For because</b></col>, <cd>because.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Nor <xex>for because</xex> they set less
store by their own citizens.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Robynson (More's Utopia).</au>
-- <col><b>For why</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Why; for that reason;
wherefore.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Because.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <see>See <er>Forwhy</er>.</see></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Because</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>For</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: For
<hw>For</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who takes, or that which is said
on, the affrimative side; that which is said in favor of some one or
something; -- the antithesis of <xex>against</xex>, and commonly used in
connection with it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The fors and against</b></col>. <cd>those in favor and
those opposed; the pros and the cons; the advantages and the
disadvantages.</cd> <rj><au>Jane Austen.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forage</ent>⟦br⟧
